After putting on the finishing touches, Pliny read it for three successive days to an audience oi his friends, who professed to enjoy it. It was only fair on their part tc say so, for he was always infinitely obliging about listening to the literary productioris of other people, Except for this solitary extant specimen we might have entertained a higher opiniones his oratory. Public recitatione, which had begun in the time of Augustus, had long been a recognized institution. Aspirants to literary fame hired a public room, filled it with an audience of their friends, and there recited and declaimed. The occupationes the real orator being taken from him hythe changed political conditions of the age, the rhetorician had usurped his place. Reputation was measured by the size of
